Well, VertxServer::stop (gRPC) does a bunch of Vert.x context magic 

```
    void stop(ContextInternal context, Promise<Void> promise) {
      boolean shutdown = count.decrementAndGet() == 0;
      context.runOnContext(v -> {
        group.removeWorker(context.nettyEventLoop());
        contextLocal.get().remove(context);
        if (shutdown) {
          map.remove(id);
          context.executeBlocking(p -> {
            server.shutdown();
            p.complete();
          }, promise);
        } else {
          promise.complete();
        }
      });
    }
```

... but I don't see how Kafka Streams could mess this up, if used together with gRPC.

>> If we change quarkus.grpc.server.use-separate-server to false (default is true) then the issue does not happen.

This is (probably) expected, as then there is only one HTTP(s) server, aka no VertxServer.
